# Global Rules

## 1. Architecture Preference
Prefer Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) for backend design.
Avoid unnecessary functional decomposition in backend domain logic.

---

## 2. SOLID Principles
All backend code must follow SOLID principles.

---

## 3. Testing Philosophy
All code must follow the TDD Core defined in:
rules/testing/tdd-core.mdc

No production code is valid unless it is validated by tests.

---

## 4. Behavior-Driven Design
Features must be described using behavior-first thinking (Given / When / Then).

Focus on observable outcomes, not implementation details.

---

## 5. Domain Isolation
Frontend and backend must remain strictly separated:

- Backend contains domain logic and business rules
- Frontend contains only UI and presentation logic
- No cross-domain logic leakage allowed

---

## 6. Design Constraint Rule
All code must prioritize clarity and correctness over abstraction.
Avoid unnecessary patterns or complexity unless justified by domain needs.

---

## 7. Rule Priority System (RPS)

When rules conflict, they must be resolved using the following priority order:

### P0 — Global Invariants
- TDD Core (rules/testing/tdd-core.mdc)
- SOLID principles
- BDD behavior rules
- OOP preference
- Domain isolation rules

### P1 — Architecture Rules
- Backend architecture rules
- Frontend architecture rules

### P2 — Design Patterns (Optional Tools)
- Backend patterns
- Frontend patterns

### P3 — Skills / Workflows
- TDD red/green/refactor skills
- BDD scenario generation
- refactor workflows

---

### Rule Resolution Principle
Higher priority rules ALWAYS override lower priority rules.

If two rules conflict:
- Follow the rule with the highest priority level
- Adapt or ignore the lower priority rule